  "prompt": "Why does acetone break down cell membranes?",
  "response": "Acetone can break down cell membranes due to its chemical properties. Here's a detailed explanation:\n\n1. **Solvent Properties**: Acetone is a polar aprotic solvent. This means it can dissolve both polar and non-polar substances to some extent. Cell membranes are composed primarily of lipids (non-polar) and proteins (which can have polar and non-polar regions). Acetone can interact with these components, disrupting their structure.\n\n2. **Lipid Bilayer Disruption**: The main component of cell membranes is the lipid bilayer, which consists of phospholipids. The hydrophobic (non-polar) tails of these phospholipids face inward, while the hydrophilic (polar) heads face outward. Acetone can penetrate this bilayer because it can dissolve the non-polar tails, leading to the disintegration of the membrane's structure.\n\n3. **Protein Denaturation**: Proteins embedded in the cell membrane can also be affected by acetone. Acetone can disrupt the hydrogen bonds and other non-covalent interactions that maintain the protein's secondary, tertiary, and quaternary structures. This denaturation can impair the function of membrane proteins, further compromising the integrity of the cell membrane.\n\n4. **Hydrophobic Interactions**: Acetone's ability to dissolve hydrophobic substances allows it to interfere with the hydrophobic interactions that are crucial for maintaining the structure of the lipid bilayer. By dissolving these hydrophobic components, acetone can cause the membrane to become more permeable and eventually break down.\n\nIn summary, acetone's ability to dissolve both polar and non-polar substances, disrupt lipid bilayers, denature proteins, and interfere with hydrophobic interactions makes it effective at breaking down cell membranes.",
